─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PREAMBLE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

This software is free for people. It is not free for profit.

If you use this work — or any modified, extended, or derived version of it —
to generate revenue, you owe a share of that revenue to the people who built
it. This applies regardless of how much the code was changed. If this work
is in the chain, its authors are in the chain.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DEFINITIONS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"Founder"
    The original author of the project, as identified in the CONTRIBUTORS
    file. The Founder holds 100% of ownership rights unless explicitly
    transferred under the terms of this license. The Founder may operate
    under a pseudonym; their legal identity is recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS
    file under the Name field and may be disclosed to establish authorship
    in legal proceedings.

"Contributor"
    Any person who has made a meaningful contribution — defined as
    implementing features, fixing bugs, or making non-trivial code changes —
    and who is listed in the CONTRIBUTORS file.

"Meaningful Contribution"
    A contribution of features, fixes, or substantive code changes. Changes
    limited to documentation, formatting, or comments do not qualify.
    Any portion of a contribution that was generated by an artificial
    intelligence tool — including code generation, completion, or
    transformation tools — is not considered the contributor's original work
    for the purposes of this license. Such AI-generated portions
    are deemed to be the Founder's contribution.

"AI-Generated Portion"
    Any part of a contribution that was produced, wholly or partly, by an
    artificial intelligence tool, regardless of how much the contributor
    prompted, edited, guided, or subsequently modified the output. Post-
    generation editing — including partial or substantial rewrites of the
    AI-generated text — does not change the classification of the original
    output; code that originated from an AI tool remains AI-generated for the
    purposes of this license. The contributor bears the burden of disclosing
    AI-generated portions at the time of submission. The required form and
    location of that disclosure are defined in clause 43.

"Ownership"
    The right to make decisions about the project, including merging
    contributions, changing the license, and transferring ownership. Ownership
    is expressed as a percentage and grants proportional voting rights and
    proportional patent holdings. Ownership is separate from revenue share.

"Revenue Share"
    The portion of commercial revenue a party is entitled to receive under a
    commercial agreement. Defined per contributor in the CONTRIBUTORS file.

"Patent Holdings"
    The proportional stake in any patents covering the software, held in
    accordance with ownership percentage. Patent holdings follow ownership
    changes automatically.

"Floor"
    A minimum percentage of ownership or revenue that is guaranteed to a
    party and cannot be diluted by the addition of new contributors. Floors
    are recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS file using the [x%] notation.

"Undiluted Share"
    A revenue share or ownership percentage that is locked and exempt from
    dilution when new contributors are added. Recorded explicitly in the
    CONTRIBUTORS file.

"Dilutable Share"
    A revenue share or ownership percentage that is reduced proportionally
    when new contributors are added to the distributable pool.

"Distributable Pool (Revenue)"
    The portion of revenue available for distribution among contributors.
    Calculated as: 100% minus the Founder's revenue floor, minus the sum
    of all undiluted revenue shares.

"Distributable Pool (Ownership)"
    The portion of ownership available for distribution among contributors.
    Calculated as: 100% minus the Founder's ownership floor, minus the sum
    of all undiluted ownership shares.

"Quorum"
    The minimum participation requirement for a valid vote. Quorum is met
    when owners holding at least 50% of total ownership have cast a ballot
    (YES, NO, ABSTAIN, or EXCUSED). An owner who is automatically marked
    ABSENT has not cast a ballot and does not count toward quorum. ABSENT is
    recorded by the system after the deadline, not cast by the owner; it
    carries no participation credit. If the voting window expires without
    quorum being met, the vote is void and must be re-opened. Quorum must be
    met before a resolution can pass.

"Resolution"
    A vote outcome. A resolution passes when yes votes exceed no votes,
    with abstentions and excused ballots excluded from the count.

"Voting Window"
    The period during which owners must cast their ballot. The default
    window is 7 days. The proposer may extend it but not shorten it below
    48 hours. The window opens when the vote record file is committed to
    the repository.

"Key Rotation Window"
    A shortened voting window that applies exclusively to GPG key rotation
    votes under clause 44, replacing the standard Voting Window in full.
    The maximum duration is 24 hours; there is no minimum floor. The proposer
    may shorten it but not extend it beyond 24 hours. The window opens when
    the vote record file is committed to the repository.

"Commercial Agent"
    A person designated by the Founder in the CONTRIBUTORS file to negotiate
    and execute commercial agreements on the Founder's behalf, within any
    scope constraints recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS file. A Commercial Agent
    may not modify the terms of this license, transfer ownership, or alter
    revenue shares. Designation and removal of a Commercial Agent require a
    resolution vote, except that before ownership is shared the Founder may
    act unilaterally consistent with clause 6. The mechanics of designation
    and scope recording are defined in clause 45.

"Declared Absence"
    A period during which an ownership holder has notified the other ownership
    holders in advance — via a commit to the repository or a message to the
    email addresses of all other owners on record — that they will be
    unavailable for a defined interval. The notification must be given at
    least 48 hours before the opening of any vote for that vote to be covered
    by the absence. A notification given after a vote has already opened does
    not excuse the holder from that vote. Votes that close during a declared
    absence do not count toward that holder's absence track, dormancy clock,
    or any participation metric. A declared absence may not exceed 6 months
    per calendar year in aggregate without a resolution vote to extend it.
    An extension vote follows the standard governance process. The owner
    requesting the extension may cast their ballot before their absence
    begins or, if already absent, may participate in the extension vote
    without losing their EXCUSED status for that vote. The extension vote
    may not itself be called during the absence it is meant to extend;
    it must be opened and concluded before the 6-month limit is reached.
    If the extension vote fails or is not called in time, any votes that
    close after the 6-month limit is reached are governed by the standard
    absence and abstention tracking rules.

"Founder Dormancy"
    A condition that arises when the Founder has accumulated 3 or more
    consecutive ABSENT votes — excluding any votes that closed during a
    declared absence — and no Commercial Agent has been designated.
    The consecutive ABSENT count resets to zero whenever the Founder casts
    any ballot (YES, NO, ABSTAIN) or is marked EXCUSED in a vote. Being
    marked EXCUSED resets the consecutive ABSENT count but does not resolve
    the Founder Dormancy condition; dormancy ends only when the Founder
    casts an active ballot (YES, NO, or ABSTAIN).

"Permanent Incapacitation"
    A condition certified in writing by a licensed physician stating that the
    holder is permanently unable to manage their affairs. Self-declaration does
    not constitute permanent incapacitation under this license.

"Absence Track"
    A per-owner counter tracking votes where the owner was marked ABSENT.
    A stripping vote may be called against an owner once their absence track
    reaches 2.

    Mid-cycle decrement: each time an owner casts a YES or NO ballot, their
    absence track is decremented by 1 (minimum 0), applied when the vote
    closes. One ballot undoes one step — clearing 2 accumulated absences
    requires 2 consecutive YES or NO ballots. Both the absence track and
    the abstention track decrement simultaneously and atomically from the
    same ballot; they are not applied sequentially.

    Full reset: both the absence track and the abstention track of the
    owner who was the subject of the stripping vote reset to zero after
    that stripping vote resolves, regardless of outcome. No other owner's
    tracks are affected by this reset. See clause 23.

"Abstention Track"
    A per-owner counter tracking votes where the owner voted ABSTAIN.
    A stripping vote may be called against an owner once their abstention
    track reaches 4.

    Mid-cycle decrement: each time an owner casts a YES or NO ballot, their
    abstention track is decremented by 1 (minimum 0), applied atomically
    alongside any absence track decrement when the vote closes. One ballot
    undoes one step in each track simultaneously — clearing 4 accumulated
    abstentions requires 4 consecutive YES or NO ballots.

    Full reset: both the abstention track and the absence track of the
    owner who was the subject of the stripping vote reset to zero after
    that stripping vote resolves, regardless of outcome. No other owner's
    tracks are affected by this reset. See clause 23.

"Participation Score"
    A combined participation metric derived from an owner's current track
    values at any point in time:

        Score = (Absence Track × 2) + Abstention Track

    The score is not stored in the CONTRIBUTORS file. Tracks are recorded
    exclusively in warning files (see clause 23); the formula governs at all
    times.

    A stripping vote may be called against an owner once their score reaches
    3, independent of the individual track thresholds defined under Absence
    Track and Abstention Track. The score threshold is the primary trigger
    and will typically fire before the individual track thresholds; the
    individual track thresholds serve as independent fallback triggers in
    cases where a single type of non-participation dominates.

    The score of the owner who was the subject of a stripping vote resets
    to zero — together with both their tracks — after that stripping vote
    resolves, regardless of outcome, as defined in clause 23. No other owner's
    score is affected by this reset. No other event resets the score directly;
    all score changes are the result of track changes applied under the rules above.

"Governance Artifact"
    Any file that forms part of the official governance record, including
    vote records, proposed CONTRIBUTORS files, ballots, signatures, warning
    files, notice records, acknowledgement files, and related hashes or
    metadata stored under the governance/ folder.

"Emergency Key Replacement"
    The process defined in clause 44 by which any other ownership holder may
    call a key rotation vote on behalf of an ownership holder whose registered
    GPG key has been compromised such that the holder can no longer sign a
    ballot to initiate the rotation themselves. The affected holder is excused
    from casting a ballot in that vote and no participation penalty is applied.

"Fork"
    Any copy of this software's source code — whether obtained by cloning,
    downloading, archiving, or any other means — that is developed,
    maintained, or distributed independently from the original project
    repository. A fork comes into existence at the moment any independent
    modification is made to the copied code, or at the moment it is first
    distributed independently, whichever occurs first. A derivative work is
    a fork for all purposes of this license.

    A private copy used solely for reading or evaluation, with no
    modifications and no distribution, is not a fork. The moment any change
    is made to the copied code — regardless of whether that change is
    distributed — the copy becomes a fork and must comply with clause 26.
    Parties who wish to modify this software must either contribute directly
    to the original project or obtain an approved legitimate fork via the
    process defined in clause 26b; private modification outside those paths
    is not permitted under this license.

