─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CONDITIONS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. ATTRIBUTION
   All distributions — original or modified — must retain this license and
   credit all authors listed in the CONTRIBUTORS file.

2. SHARE-ALIKE
   Any fork of this software — including any modified or derived version, as
   defined under the Fork definition — must be released under this same license
   (PBL v2.0, or any later version approved by a resolution vote of the
   project's ownership holders, provided such later version is a published,
   publicly available revision of PBL issued by the original license author
   or, if the original license author is deceased, by their designated
   Successor-Revenue or legal heirs acting as custodian of the license).
   Each project governs its own version upgrade independently: the original
   project's ownership holders decide which version applies to the original
   project; a legitimate fork's ownership holders decide which version applies
   to the fork. A version upgrade in one project has no effect on the other.

3. COMMERCIAL USE REQUIRES AGREEMENT
   "Commercial use" means any use where this software, or a derivative of it,
   is a direct or material input to generating revenue. "Material input" means
   the software contributes in a non-trivial way to the functionality, cost
   reduction, or output that drives the revenue in question. Incidental or
   isolated use that has no measurable effect on any revenue-generating
   activity is not a material input. Where the parties dispute whether use
   is a material input, the use is presumed to be commercial unless the
   party asserting non-commercial use demonstrates in writing that the
   software has no measurable effect on any revenue-generating activity.
   Use is commercial when any of the following apply:

     - The software, or a product that includes it, is sold or licensed for
       a fee
     - The software is used to operate a paid service, SaaS, or subscription
       product
     - The software is deployed internally at a for-profit organisation in a
       capacity that directly reduces operating costs or directly increases
       output in the organisation's revenue-generating activities
     - The software is incorporated into a larger product that is sold or
       monetised, and the software's functionality is materially present in
       the value offered to customers

   Use is NOT commercial solely because:
     - An employee of a for-profit company uses the software for personal
       learning or evaluation, without deploying it in any company product
       or workflow
     - The software is used in academic or non-profit research, even if that
       research is funded by a grant from a for-profit entity

   If your use is commercial, you must contact the Founder (see CONTACT
   section at the end of this license) before deploying and negotiate a
   revenue-share agreement. No fixed percentage is set here — terms are
   agreed between parties. Operating commercially without an agreement is a
   violation of this license.

   "Before deploying" means before the software first contributes to any
   revenue-generating activity as defined above. There is no grace period
   based on revenue amount, number of customers, or business stage. For any
   organisation — including incorporated entities, partnerships, and sole
   traders operating under any business structure — internal use that reduces
   costs or increases output in revenue-generating operations triggers the
   requirement upon first such use, regardless of whether any external
   customer has yet been served.

   Where the software is incorporated into a product by one party and that
   product is then sold or operated by a different party, each party whose
   independent use satisfies the commercial use definition above must
   independently obtain a commercial agreement with the Founder.

   Commercial agreements are valid for the duration specified in the
   agreement. If no duration is specified, the agreement is valid for one
   year from the date of execution and must be renewed to remain in effect.
   If a licensee ceases to make payments required under a commercial
   agreement, the Founder must notify the licensee in writing at the contact
   address on record. If the outstanding amounts are not paid within 14 days
   of that notice, all rights granted by the agreement are suspended
   automatically. Suspension is not a permanent revocation — rights are
   restored upon payment of all outstanding amounts. The Founder may convert
   a suspension into permanent termination of the commercial agreement by
   written notice to the licensee, effective immediately upon delivery of
   that notice. Termination under this paragraph does not affect the
   Founder's right to pursue remedies for the period of unlicensed use
   under clause 33.

   Payment terms — including the specific percentage of revenue owed, the
   payment frequency, currency, and method — are defined in each commercial
   agreement. Non-cash consideration (including equity, barter, or in-kind
   exchange) must be valued at fair market value in a mutually agreed
   currency at the time of the agreement. This license does not prescribe
   payment terms; it requires only that a valid commercial agreement
   governing those terms exists before any commercial use begins.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
OWNERSHIP
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

4. COPYRIGHT
   Copyright remains solely with the Founder regardless of the number or
   significance of contributions made by others. Contributing to this project
   does not transfer, share, or diminish the Founder's copyright.

5. PSEUDONYMITY
   Authors and contributors may operate under a pseudonym. The use of a
   pseudonym does not affect the validity of copyright, ownership, or revenue
   entitlements established under this license. Legal names are recorded
   privately in the CONTRIBUTORS file under the Name field and may be
   disclosed solely for the purpose of establishing identity in legal
   proceedings. No party is required to disclose their legal identity
   publicly.

6. OWNERSHIP PERCENTAGE
   Ownership is tracked in the CONTRIBUTORS file. The Founder begins at 100%
   ownership. Ownership may be transferred to a contributor only via
   resolution vote and the governance process defined in clauses 19–25.
   Transferred ownership is drawn proportionally from all existing dilutable
   ownership shares in the distributable ownership pool. Since the Founder
   holds 100% ownership by default, the Founder may pass any resolution
   unilaterally until ownership is shared. This principle applies wherever
   a resolution vote is required by this license.

7. FOUNDER OWNERSHIP FLOOR
   The Founder is guaranteed a minimum ownership of 30% at all times. This
   is the default floor. The floor cannot be diluted by the addition of
   contributors. It ensures the Founder retains meaningful voting power
   regardless of how much ownership is shared. The floor may be changed
   only by resolution vote, and the new value must be recorded in the
   CONTRIBUTORS file.

8. VOTING
   All project decisions are governed by a vote among ownership holders.
   Any owner may call a vote, subject to the restrictions below. A vote
   passes when quorum is met and yes votes exceed no votes after all ballots
   are cast or the voting window expires. Abstentions are excluded from the
   count. If yes votes equal no votes, the side that the Founder voted for
   wins; if the Founder abstained, did not vote, was marked ABSENT, or is
   not a party to the vote, the vote fails. For the purposes of the
   tie-break rule, an ABSENT Founder is treated the same as a Founder who
   did not vote. If the Founder holds zero ownership at the time of a vote —
   whether through transfer or a floor of zero — the Founder has no voting
   rights in that vote and is not a party for the purposes of the tie-break
   rule; a tie fails regardless of any prior vote by the Founder. If quorum
   is not met when the voting window expires, the vote is void. All votes
   must be recorded and verified via the
   governance process defined in clauses 19–25. See clause 6 for the
   Founder's unilateral resolution right prior to ownership being shared.

   Voting rights:
     Only ownership holders with a non-zero ownership percentage have voting
     rights. Contributors holding a revenue share but zero ownership have no
     governance rights under this license and may not call or vote on any
     resolution.

   Minimum ownership to call a vote:
     A non-Founder owner must hold at least 5% ownership at the time they
     open a vote. The Founder is exempt from this requirement.

   Cooldown:
     A non-Founder owner may not open a new vote until at least 30 days
     have elapsed since the closing date of the last vote they opened. The
     Founder is exempt from this requirement.

     Per-subject cooldown:
     No owner — including the Founder — may open a vote on the same subject
     as a vote that closed within the preceding 30 days and produced a
     tally (passed or failed). A vote that was void for lack of quorum does
     not trigger the cooldown; it may be re-opened immediately. Two votes
     share the same subject when their slugs are identical or when a
     reasonable reader would conclude they concern the same specific
     decision. The Founder may waive this restriction for urgent matters
     by stating the reason in the vote record.

   Ballot options:
     YES         — in favour of the proposed change
     NO          — against the proposed change
     ABSTAIN     — present but not counted on either side
     ABSENT      — did not vote before the deadline; recorded automatically
     EXCUSED     — did not vote due to a declared absence; recorded
                   automatically; no penalty applied

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PATENTS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

9. PATENT OWNERSHIP
   Patents covering the software are held proportionally to ownership
   percentage as recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS file. By submitting a
   contribution, the contributor irrevocably assigns to the existing
   ownership pool all patent rights covering the specific code, algorithms,
   or inventions embodied in their submitted contribution — and any
   improvements to that contribution made within the project repository —
   distributed proportionally among current owners. This assignment is
   limited to inventions directly present in the submitted contribution; it
   does not extend to any other work or invention by the contributor outside
   the scope of the contribution. Patent holdings follow ownership changes
   automatically — when ownership is transferred via resolution vote, patent
   holdings adjust accordingly.

10. PATENT LICENSE TO USERS
    Owners grant all users a non-exclusive, worldwide, royalty-free patent
    license to use the software for non-commercial purposes only, to the
    extent of their patent holdings. No patent license is granted for
    commercial use beyond what is negotiated in a commercial agreement.
    Enforcement of any patent covering this software requires a majority
    ownership vote.

11. NO SUBLICENSING OF PATENTS
    Patent licenses granted under this license are personal and
    non-transferable. No party may sublicense, assign, or transfer their
    patent rights or patent license to any third party without a resolution vote.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REVENUE SHARE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

12. FOUNDER REVENUE FLOOR
    The Founder is guaranteed a minimum revenue share of 30% on every
    commercial agreement. This is the default floor. The floor cannot be
    diluted by the addition of contributors. The floor may be changed only
    by resolution vote, and the new value must be recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS
    file.

13. CONTRIBUTOR REVENUE SHARE
    Contributors listed in the CONTRIBUTORS file are entitled to a share of
    commercial revenue as recorded therein. A contributor's share takes
    effect only upon being listed in the CONTRIBUTORS file. Listing always
    requires a resolution vote following a meaningful contribution. A
    contributor's share may be dilutable or undiluted, and may include a
    floor, as determined by the resolution vote at the time of listing. See
    clause 6 for the Founder's unilateral resolution right prior to
    ownership being shared.

14. REVENUE DILUTION
    When a new contributor is added to the distributable revenue pool, their
    share is drawn proportionally from all existing dilutable revenue shares —
    the Founder's revenue above their floor and all non-undiluted contributor
    shares — reducing each in proportion to its current size. Undiluted shares
    and floors are exempt from this reduction.

15. OWNERSHIP DILUTION
    When ownership is transferred to a contributor via resolution vote, the
    transferred percentage is drawn proportionally from all existing dilutable
    ownership shares — the Founder's ownership above their floor and all
    non-undiluted contributor ownership shares — reducing each in proportion
    to its current size. Undiluted ownership shares and floors are exempt from
    this reduction.

16. CONTRIBUTOR FLOORS AND UNDILUTED SHARES
    A resolution vote may grant any contributor a floor and/or an undiluted
    share on their revenue, ownership, or both, as recognition of
    exceptional or significant contribution. All such grants must be
    recorded explicitly in the CONTRIBUTORS file and verified via the
    governance process defined in clauses 19–25. Floors and undiluted shares
    granted to contributors follow the same mechanics as the Founder's
    floor: exempt from dilution, recorded with the [x%] notation. See
    clause 6 for the Founder's unilateral resolution right prior to
    ownership being shared.

17. NO SUBLICENSING
    Commercial agreements are personal and non-transferable. A commercial
    licensee may not sublicense, resell, assign, or transfer their commercial
    agreement or any rights granted thereunder to any third party. Any
    attempted sublicense or transfer is void and constitutes a violation of
    this license.

    Change of control: in the event of a merger, acquisition, asset purchase,
    or any other transaction resulting in a change of control of a commercial
    licensee — regardless of whether the licensee's legal entity survives the
    transaction — the licensee must notify the Founder in writing within 30
    days of the change of control. The commercial agreement is suspended from
    the date the change of control takes effect. The affected entity may
    continue to operate under the terms of the suspended agreement for up to
    30 days from the date of the change of control (not from the date of
    notification) while a new agreement is negotiated, provided written
    notification has been given. Failure to notify within 30 days forfeits
    any grace period and the suspension becomes effective immediately upon
    the change of control. If no new agreement is executed within 30 days of
    the change of control, the suspended agreement terminates automatically
    and all commercial rights cease. Operating beyond that window under a
    suspended agreement without executing a new agreement constitutes a
    commercial violation under clause 33.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CONTRIBUTORS FILE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

18. CONTRIBUTORS FILE
    Every project under this license must maintain a CONTRIBUTORS file at the
    root of the repository. This file is the authoritative record of
    ownership percentages, revenue shares, patent holdings, floors, undiluted
    status, participation tracking, and succession. Its format is defined in
    this license and must be followed exactly.

    The CONTRIBUTORS file format is:

    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
     CONTRIBUTORS
    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

     Authoritative record of ownership and revenue shares for this project.
     Governed by the PayBack License (PBL) v2.0.

    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     LEGEND
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

     ⁕     founder
     [x%]  undiluted floor

    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     SUMMARY                                    OWNERSHIP    REVENUE
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

     ⁕ Founder Pseudonym                        100% [30%]   100% [30%]
       Contributor Pseudonym                       0%          12% [8%]
       Contributor Pseudonym                       0%           8%

    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     DETAILS
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

     ⁕ Founder Pseudonym
       Pseudonym            Founder Pseudonym
       Name                 Legal Name
       Role                 Founder
       Email                founder@example.com
       GPG                  AABB CCDD EEFF 0011 2233 4455 6677 8899 AABB CCDD
       Ownership            100% [30%]
       Revenue              100% [30%]
       Commercial-Agent     (optional)
       Successor-Ownership  (optional)
       Successor-Revenue    (optional)

       Contributor Pseudonym
       Pseudonym            Contributor Pseudonym
       Name                 Legal Name
       Role                 Contributor
       Email                contrib@example.com
       GPG                  1122 3344 5566 7788 99AA BBCC DDEE FF00 1122 3344
       Ownership              0%
       Revenue               12% [8%]
       Successor-Revenue    (optional)

    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

    Field definitions:

      ⁕           Founder marker
      [x%]        Undiluted floor — this share cannot be diluted by new
                  contributors
      SUMMARY     Quick-reference table of all ownership and revenue shares
      DETAILS     Full entry per contributor with contact and GPG key
      Pseudonym   Public identity used in authorship, attribution, and
                  project artifacts; may differ from the legal name
      Name        Full legal name; used to establish identity in legal
                  proceedings; may differ from the pseudonym
      Role        Founder or Contributor
      Email       Contact address
      GPG         Full GPG key fingerprint used to sign ballots
      Ownership   Current ownership percentage granting voting rights and
                  proportional patent holdings; total must equal 100%;
                  bracketed value is the floor
      Revenue     Current revenue share percentage; all values are resolved
                  — no dynamic placeholders; bracketed value is the floor
      Commercial-Agent     Present only on the Founder's entry. Optional;
                           pseudonym or legal name of the person authorised to
                           negotiate and execute commercial agreements on the
                           Founder's behalf, as defined in clause 45. May
                           include a scope constraint in parentheses after the
                           name. If blank, no Commercial Agent is designated.
      Successor-Ownership  Present only if the holder has a non-zero ownership
                           percentage or patent holdings. Optional; pseudonym or
                           legal name of the person who inherits the ownership
                           stake and patent holdings upon death or permanent
                           incapacitation. If blank, these pass to the holder's
                           legal heirs.
      Successor-Revenue    Present only if the holder has a non-zero revenue
                           share. Optional; pseudonym or legal name of the
                           person who inherits the revenue share upon death or
                           permanent incapacitation. If blank, the revenue share
                           passes to the holder's legal heirs. May name a
                           different person than Successor-Ownership.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
GOVERNANCE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

19. GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE
    The reference implementation for managing governance artifacts is Voto,
    a CLI and GUI tool that automates the creation, signing, verification,
    and closing of votes. Its use is recommended but not required.
    All governance artifacts are stored in the governance/ folder at the
    root of the repository, organised as follows:

      governance/
        votes/
          <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/
            <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.vote
            CONTRIBUTORS.proposed         (only if vote modifies CONTRIBUTORS)
            <fingerprint>.ballot          (clearsigned; one per voter)
            <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.seal        (clearsigned; one per vote; updated after each ballot)
            <fingerprint>.tally           (clearsigned; secret votes only; one per voter)
            <fingerprint>.excused         (clearsigned; only if EXCUSED)
            ...
        warnings/
          <YYYY-MM-DD>_warning-<absent|abstain>-<pseudonym>.warn
        notices/
          <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.notice
          <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/
            CONTRIBUTORS.proposed
            <fingerprint>.ack             (clearsigned; one per owner)
            ...

20. VOTE RECORD FORMAT
    All project votes must be recorded as a vote record file, regardless
    of whether they modify the CONTRIBUTORS file.

    Each vote must concern exactly one subject. Bundling multiple unrelated
    decisions into a single vote is not permitted. The only permitted
    exceptions are:

      a) A combined ownership-and-revenue stripping vote under clause 24,
         where both are explicitly stated in the vote description and the
         vote slug.
      b) A legitimate fork vote under clause 26b that bundles the fork's
         proposed CONTRIBUTORS file with the original project's revised
         CONTRIBUTORS file, where both are explicitly stated in the vote
         description and the vote slug.

    The slug must be a concise, descriptive, kebab-case phrase that
    unambiguously identifies the subject and outcome of the vote, such that
    the filename alone conveys the nature of the decision to an uninformed
    reader (e.g. add-jane-doe-as-contributor,
    change-founder-revenue-floor-to-40pct,
    approve-commercial-agreement-with-acme).

    The vote record file is sealed at creation — it must not be modified
    after it is first committed to the repository. The proposer seals it
    by committing two files simultaneously when opening the vote:

      1. A clearsigned ballot file using their own GPG key, stored as:
           governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<proposer-fingerprint>.ballot
         This file serves as both the proposer's seal of the .vote record and,
         if the proposer is an ownership holder, their own vote.

      2. The initial seal file, stored as:
           governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.seal
         At opening, the proposer produces the innermost seal layer containing
         their ballot entry and signs it with their registered key. Subsequent
         voters each wrap the entire file with an additional signature layer.
         The seal format is defined in clause 21a.

    Any modification to the .vote file after the initial commit constitutes
    bad-faith governance under clause 32. The current tally is derived solely
    from the .ballot files present in the vote folder; no separate ballot
    summary is maintained in the .vote file. The vote record must follow this
    format:

    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
     VOTE
    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

     <description of the decision — the headline of the vote>

    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     METADATA
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

     Opened     <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>
     Opened-by  <Pseudonym of the owner who called the vote>
     Deadline   <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>
     Secret     <yes | no>            (default: yes)

     Files
       <filename>   <BLAKE3 hash>
       ...

    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     OWNERSHIP SNAPSHOT
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

     <Pseudonym>   <ownership %>
     ...

    ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

    The Files section lists every file relevant to the vote that must be
    present in the vote folder. Each file is listed with its BLAKE3 hash
    so that any party can verify the exact content that was voted on.
    For votes that modify CONTRIBUTORS, CONTRIBUTORS.proposed must be
    listed. The Files section may be omitted for votes with no associated
    files.

    The Secret field declares whether the vote uses the secret ballot
    process defined in clause 21b. If Secret is yes, or if the field is
    omitted, the vote uses commit-reveal ballots and the tally process
    defined in clause 21b applies in full. If Secret is no, the vote
    uses the standard public ballot format defined in clause 21.
    The Secret field is fixed at creation and may not be changed after
    the vote record is first committed.

21. BALLOT FORMAT
    Each owner casts their vote by creating a clearsigned ballot file. The
    plaintext content of the ballot must be:

      Pseudonym  <pseudonym>
      Vote       <YES | NO | ABSTAIN>
      Vote-on    <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Vote-hash  <BLAKE3 hash of the sealed .vote file>
      Timestamp  <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>

    The file is produced with gpg --clearsign, yielding a single file with
    the plaintext content and the GPG signature block inline. It is stored as:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<fingerprint>.ballot

    The Vote-hash must match the BLAKE3 hash of the .vote file as first
    committed. All valid ballots carry the same Vote-hash value. A ballot
    whose Vote-hash does not match the sealed .vote file is invalid. No
    further modifications to the .vote file are made after casting.

    After committing their ballot file, the voter must immediately update the
    seal by adding their signature layer, as defined in clause 21a.

21a. SEAL FORMAT
    A seal file is created for every vote — public and secret — by the proposer
    at the moment the vote is opened, and extended by each voter immediately
    after their ballot is committed. The seal accumulates one GPG clearsign
    layer per participant: each voter runs gpg --clearsign over the entire
    current seal file — plaintext body and all prior signature layers included
    — producing a new file that wraps all previous content. The ordering of
    layers reflects the chronological order in which participants signed.
    Tamper evidence is structural: altering any inner layer invalidates all
    outer signatures that wrap it.

    The seal file is stored as:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.seal

    There is a single seal file per vote. Each time a participant adds their
    layer, the file grows. No prior content is discarded or overwritten.

    The innermost plaintext layer — produced by the proposer at vote open —
    must contain:

      Vote-on    <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Vote-hash  <BLAKE3 hash of the .vote file as first committed>
      Opened     <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>
      Opened-by  <proposer's pseudonym>
      Ballots
        <fingerprint>   <BLAKE3 hash of the corresponding .ballot file>
        ...

    Each subsequent layer added by a voter wraps the entire current seal file
    and its plaintext must contain:

      Vote-on    <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Vote-hash  <BLAKE3 hash of the .vote file as first committed>
      Updated    <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>
      Updated-by <voter's pseudonym>
      Ballots
        <fingerprint>   <BLAKE3 hash of the corresponding .ballot file>
        ...

    The Ballots section in every layer lists every ballot file present in the
    vote folder at the time that layer was signed, including the one just
    submitted. Each entry is identified by the voter's key fingerprint and the
    BLAKE3 hash of their ballot file. Every layer is produced with
    gpg --clearsign using the signing party's registered key.

    The seal is valid when, after peeling all layers from outermost to
    innermost using compliant tooling:
      - Each layer's GPG signature verifies correctly against the registered
        key of the party named in that layer's Updated-by (or Opened-by for
        the innermost layer)
      - The Vote-hash field in every layer matches the BLAKE3 hash of the
        .vote file as first committed to the repository
      - The Ballots section in each layer contains every ballot present at
        the time that layer was signed, with correct BLAKE3 hashes
      - No ballot entry present in an inner layer is missing or altered in
        any outer layer
      - The layers are ordered chronologically from innermost to outermost

    Verification of a stacked seal requires compliant tooling (such as Voto)
    capable of peeling and verifying nested GPG clearsign layers. Manual
    gpg --verify will verify only the outermost layer; full seal verification
    requires all layers to be peeled and checked individually.

    A ballot file whose fingerprint and BLAKE3 hash do not appear in the
    outermost valid seal layer is invalid for tally and quorum purposes, even
    if the file is physically present in the vote folder.

    An owner who commits a ballot but fails to add their seal layer is in
    breach of the governance process. The proposer may add a seal layer on
    that owner's behalf, listing the owner's ballot in the Ballots section
    and signing with the proposer's own key; if neither party adds a layer
    within 24 hours of the ballot being committed, the ballot is invalid.

21b. SECRET BALLOT FORMAT
    A vote declared with Secret: yes uses a two-phase commit-reveal process.
    The ballot file carries a cryptographic commitment to the voter's choice
    instead of the choice itself; the choice is revealed only after the voting
    window closes.

    Phase 1 — Commitment (during the voting window):
    Each owner casts their vote by creating a clearsigned ballot file.
    The plaintext content of the ballot must be:

      Pseudonym   <pseudonym>
      Vote-on     <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Vote-hash   <BLAKE3 hash of the sealed .vote file>
      Commitment  <BLAKE3(choice || nonce)>
      Timestamp   <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>

    where choice is the literal string YES, NO, or ABSTAIN, and nonce
    is a secret random value of at least 128 bits, hex-encoded, known
    only to the voter. The file is produced with gpg --clearsign and
    stored as:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<fingerprint>.ballot

    After committing their ballot file, the voter must immediately add their
    seal layer as defined in clause 21a. The commitment phase is otherwise
    governed by the same rules as standard ballots: quorum is measured by
    commitments received, an owner who does not commit before the deadline
    is marked ABSENT, and excused ballots follow the mechanics defined in
    clause 23.

    The reveal window opens the moment the voting window closes. No tally
    may be submitted before the voting window has closed. A ballot whose
    fingerprint and BLAKE3 hash do not appear in the outermost valid seal
    layer at the time the voting window closes is invalid for tally purposes,
    even if the ballot file is physically present in the vote folder.

    Phase 2 — Reveal (after the voting window closes):
    A 48-hour reveal window opens when the voting window closes. Within this
    window, each owner who committed a ballot must submit a clearsigned tally
    file revealing their choice and nonce. The plaintext content of the tally
    must be:

      Pseudonym    <voter's pseudonym>
      Submitted-by <pseudonym of submitter>   (omitted if self-submitted)
      Vote-on      <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Vote-hash    <BLAKE3 hash of the sealed .vote file>
      Choice       <YES | NO | ABSTAIN>
      Nonce        <hex-encoded random value used in the commitment>
      Timestamp    <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS UTC>

    The file is produced with gpg --clearsign using the submitter's
    registered key and stored as:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<fingerprint>.tally
    where fingerprint is the submitter's key fingerprint.

    A voter may submit their own tally, or may provide their choice and
    nonce to the vote proposer, who may then submit the tally on their
    behalf. No owner other than the voter and the proposer may submit
    a tally on another voter's behalf.

    If the proposer is themselves unable to submit their own tally before
    the reveal window expires — due to incapacitation, key compromise, or
    any other reason — any other ownership holder may submit the tally on
    the proposer's behalf, provided the proposer has supplied their choice
    and nonce to that owner in writing. The substitute submitter must sign
    the tally file with their own registered key, include a Submitted-by
    field naming themselves, and attach the proposer's written disclosure
    as a clearsigned file in the same vote folder. If no owner is able or
    willing to submit the proposer's tally within the reveal window, the
    proposer is treated as ABSTAIN under the same mechanics defined for
    voters who fail to reveal.

    A tally is valid when:
      - The clearsign signature in the .tally file verifies correctly
      - The signing key fingerprint matches the registered GPG key of
        the submitter (the voter if self-submitted, or the proposer if
        submitted on behalf)
      - The Pseudonym field matches an owner who committed a valid
        .ballot file for this vote
      - The Vote-hash field matches the BLAKE3 hash of the sealed .vote
        file as first committed
      - The voter's fingerprint and ballot BLAKE3 hash appear in the outermost
        valid seal layer at the time the voting window closed
      - BLAKE3(Choice || Nonce) matches the Commitment field in the
        corresponding .ballot file exactly

    An owner whose fingerprint appears in the seal at close time but whose
    tally is not submitted — by themselves or by the proposer — before the
    reveal window expires is treated as ABSTAIN for tally purposes. Their
    abstention track is incremented and a warning file is created under
    the same mechanics defined in clause 23. This is not an additional
    penalty on top of any absence or abstention already recorded during
    the commitment phase; it applies only if the owner was not already
    marked ABSENT.

    The vote is tallied once the reveal window closes or once all
    owners who committed have submitted valid tallies, whichever comes
    first. No choice is counted until a valid tally confirms it. The
    tally is final and the result is determined by the confirmed choices
    under the same passing criteria defined in clause 22.

22. VERIFICATION
    A vote passes when quorum is met and yes votes exceed no votes after
    all owners have voted or the voting window has expired. Abstentions are
    excluded from the count. If yes votes equal no votes, the side that the
    Founder voted for wins; if the Founder abstained, did not vote, was
    marked ABSENT, or is not a party to the vote, the vote fails. An ABSENT
    Founder is treated the same as a Founder who did not vote for the
    purpose of this tie-break rule. If the voting window expires without
    quorum, the vote is void and no CONTRIBUTORS update may be made on its basis.
    A ballot is valid when:
      - The clearsign signature in the .ballot file verifies correctly
      - The signing key fingerprint matches the GPG field of the owner's
        entry in the CONTRIBUTORS file at the time of the vote
      - The pseudonym in the .ballot file matches the owner's CONTRIBUTORS
        entry
      - The owner holds a non-zero ownership percentage
      - The Vote-hash field matches the BLAKE3 hash of the sealed .vote
        file as first committed to the repository

    For secret votes, the validity and tally rules defined in clause 21b
    apply in place of the ballot content rules above. A ballot in a
    secret vote is valid when the commitment phase requirements of
    clause 21b are satisfied and the ballot's fingerprint and BLAKE3 hash appear
    in the outermost valid seal layer at the time the voting window closes;
    the final tally is determined by the reveal phase of clause 21b.
    All other passing criteria in this clause — quorum, yes-exceeds-no,
    Founder tie-break, void on expired quorum — apply unchanged.

    The CONTRIBUTORS file may only be updated after the vote passes and
    all artifacts are committed to the repository alongside it.

    Ballot disputes: if any owner believes a ballot was cast with a
    compromised or fraudulent key, they must raise the objection in writing
    to all other ownership holders before the CONTRIBUTORS file is updated
    following the vote. The objection must identify the ballot and state the
    grounds. If the objection is not resolved by agreement, the vote is
    paused and a key-rotation or bad-faith-governance process under clauses
    42 and 32 respectively must be completed before the vote may resume.
    When a paused vote resumes, the original voting window is extended by
    the duration of the pause; previously cast valid ballots remain in
    effect and owners who have not yet voted may cast their ballot during
    the extension.

23. ABSENCE AND ABSTENTION TRACKING
    If a vote closes during a declared absence for an owner — as defined in
    the Declared Absence definition — that owner is not marked ABSENT, no
    warning file is created, and no track or score is incremented for that
    vote. The owner's EXCUSED status is recorded by committing a clearsigned
    file to the vote folder as:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<fingerprint>.excused
    The plaintext content must include the owner's pseudonym, the vote slug,
    the reason (declared absence), and the absence period dates. It is
    produced with gpg --clearsign using the owner's registered key.

    After each vote, if an owner is marked ABSENT or ABSTAIN, their
    respective track is incremented and a warning file is created at:
      governance/warnings/<YYYY-MM-DD>_warning-<absent|abstain>-<pseudonym>.warn

    The warning file must follow this format:

      Pseudonym  <pseudonym>
      Reason     <absent | abstain>
      Vote       <YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>
      Absent     <absence track after incrementing>
      Abstain    <abstention track after incrementing>
      Score      <participation score after incrementing>

    Track thresholds — any of the following enables a stripping vote to
    be called; none of them mandate it (see "Participation Score" in the
    Definitions section for the score formula):
      - Absence track reaches 2
      - Abstention track reaches 4
      - Participation score reaches 3

    Mid-cycle track decrements: when a vote closes, after applying any
    absence or abstention increments for owners who were ABSENT or ABSTAIN,
    any owner who cast a YES or NO ballot in that vote has their absence
    track and abstention track each decremented by 1 (minimum 0 each),
    atomically and simultaneously. EXCUSED counts as participation for the
    purpose of decrementing the absence track by 1 (minimum 0) but does not
    decrement the abstention track and does not increment any track or score.
    This rule applies uniformly to all owners, including the Founder.
    ABSTAIN and ABSENT ballots do not trigger any decrement.

    Thresholds are prerequisites for calling a stripping vote, not automatic
    triggers. No action is required until an owner chooses to call one.
    After any stripping vote resolves — regardless of outcome — both tracks
    and the participation score of the owner who was the subject of that
    stripping vote reset to zero immediately. No other owner's tracks or
    score are affected. Any mid-cycle decrement progress is also cleared by this
    full reset.

24. OWNERSHIP STRIPPING
    Once any threshold defined in clause 23 is reached, any owner may
    call a vote to strip or reduce the flagged owner's ownership. A
    stripping vote may reduce an owner's ownership percentage down to
    their recorded floor, but never below it. The floor is the absolute
    minimum that stripping can reach; it cannot be stripped further without
    a separate resolution vote explicitly modifying the floor under clause 7.

    A stripping vote concerns ownership only by default. Revenue share is
    not affected unless the vote explicitly states that both ownership and
    revenue are being stripped, in which case the single vote may cover
    both as a permitted exception under clause 20. A vote to strip revenue
    alone, without stripping ownership, may be called at any time by any
    owner as a separate resolution vote — it does not require the ownership
    stripping thresholds in clause 23 to be met and may target any
    contributor regardless of their participation track values.

    If the stripping vote passes, the flagged owner's ownership is
    redistributed among all remaining owners proportionally to their
    existing dilutable ownership shares, following the standard dilution
    mechanics in clause 15. If revenue is also stripped, the flagged owner's
    revenue share is likewise redistributed among all remaining contributors
    proportionally to their existing dilutable revenue shares, following the
    standard dilution mechanics in clause 14.

    The stripped owner may earn ownership again through meaningful
    contribution and a subsequent resolution vote, as with any new contributor.

25. ADMINISTRATIVE NOTICE
    An Administrative Notice is a lightweight governance record used when
    the CONTRIBUTORS file must be updated to reflect an undisputed factual
    change — that is, a change whose underlying facts are not in dispute,
    as distinct from a policy decision that requires a vote. Examples of
    qualifying factual changes include: combining shares when a succession
    results in a successor who already holds ownership in the project;
    updating a GPG fingerprint following a passed key rotation vote;
    recording a pseudonym or contact-address correction agreed to by the
    affected owner. Examples of changes that do not qualify and require a
    resolution vote instead: altering any ownership or revenue percentage;
    adding or removing a contributor; modifying any floor or undiluted
    designation. A notice requires no vote but demands acknowledgement from
    all ownership holders.

    A notice record must be committed to:
      governance/notices/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>.notice

    The notice file must contain:
      - The pseudonym of the affected owner or owners
      - A plain-language description of the factual change being recorded
      - The proposed updated CONTRIBUTORS file, committed as
        CONTRIBUTORS.proposed alongside the notice file
      - The date the notice was opened
      - The acknowledgement deadline (minimum 7 days from opening)

    Each owner acknowledges by committing a clearsigned acknowledgement file
    to the notice folder, stored as:
      governance/notices/<YYYY-MM-DD>_<slug>/<fingerprint>.ack
    The plaintext content must contain the owner's pseudonym, the notice
    slug, and a UTC timestamp. It is produced with gpg --clearsign using
    the owner's registered key. Silence after the deadline constitutes
    automatic acknowledgement. Failure to acknowledge an Administrative Notice
    carries no participation penalty and does not affect any track or score
    under clause 23, regardless of how many notices are missed.

    An owner may not block an Administrative Notice. The CONTRIBUTORS file
    is updated after the deadline passes, regardless of whether all owners
    have explicitly acknowledged, provided no owner has raised a written
    objection identifying a factual error in the proposed change. An
    objection is valid only if committed to the repository before the
    acknowledgement deadline; objections raised after the deadline but before
    the CONTRIBUTORS file is updated are not recognised and do not pause the
    notice. A factual objection — not a policy objection — pauses the notice
    and triggers a resolution vote on the disputed fact. Policy disagreement
    with an undisputed fact is not grounds for objection.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORKS AND DERIVATIVES
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

26. FORK REQUIREMENTS
    Any fork of this software — including any derivative work, as defined
    under the Fork definition — must be released under this same license
    (PBL v2.0, or any later version approved by a resolution vote of
    the fork's ownership holders). A fork that does not carry over the
    inherited CONTRIBUTORS file at creation has no valid license under this
    agreement. Any distribution of such a fork — commercial or not —
    constitutes copyright infringement. The inherited CONTRIBUTORS file is a
    condition of the license grant, not a covenant.

    Where no initial independent commit is made, the CONTRIBUTORS snapshot is
    fixed at the moment the fork is first distributed independently, as stated
    in the Fork definition. The same snapshot rule applies: the last validly
    committed CONTRIBUTORS file of the original project at that moment governs.

    A fork that carries over the inherited CONTRIBUTORS file but has not been
    elevated to a legitimate independent project by a resolution vote under
    clause 26b has no rights of its own under this license. It may not enter
    commercial agreements, accept contributions, call governance votes, or
    modify its CONTRIBUTORS file independently. All governance of such a fork
    remains subject to the original project's ownership holders and the
    inherited governance structure. Any act purporting to exercise independent
    rights in such a fork — including executing a commercial agreement,
    unilaterally amending the CONTRIBUTORS file, or calling a vote outside the
    original project's governance process — is void and constitutes bad-faith
    governance under clause 32.

    The original Founder's ownership and revenue floors as recorded in the
    original project's CONTRIBUTORS file at the time of the fork carry over
    unchanged into the fork's CONTRIBUTORS file. The original Founder's
    ownership floor carried into a fork is the minimum ownership percentage
    the fork's governance may not strip below; it follows the same mechanics
    as the Founder ownership floor defined in clause 7, applied within the
    fork. The original Founder's revenue floor carried into a fork represents
    a minimum share of the fork's total commercial revenue — calculated as
    a first-priority carve-out from 100% of the fork's gross commercial
    revenue before any internal distribution among the fork's own owners and
    contributors — payable to the original Founder under the same payment,
    suspension, and termination mechanics defined in clause 3. This floor is
    not applied against the fork's internal distributable pool; it is applied
    at the top level, regardless of how the fork partitions the remainder
    among its own owners. The original Founder must be named as a payee in
    any commercial agreement the fork executes. The
    original Founder's audit right under clause 35 applies to any fork that
    has entered a commercial agreement or
    otherwise satisfies clause 3, as though the fork were a direct licensee
    of the original project.

    If the original Founder is deceased or permanently incapacitated at the
    time the fork's commercial agreement is executed, or becomes so afterward,
    the original Founder's carried-over revenue floor passes to the original
    Founder's designated Successor-Revenue as recorded in the original
    project's CONTRIBUTORS file. If no Successor-Revenue is named, the floor
    passes to the original Founder's legal heirs in accordance with applicable
    inheritance law. Until a valid successor or heir has been identified and
    confirmed in writing to the fork's ownership holders, the fork must hold
    all amounts owed under the original Founder's floor in escrow and may not
    distribute them to any other party. The fork's payment and escrow
    obligations under this paragraph follow the same mechanics as the
    payment, suspension, and termination provisions defined in clause 3.

    Once a legitimate fork's CONTRIBUTORS file is committed following a
    passing resolution vote under clause 26b, the fork and the original
    project are fully independent projects governed exclusively by their own
    respective CONTRIBUTORS files and ownership holders. This independence
    does not arise from merely committing the inherited CONTRIBUTORS file
    without a passing 26b vote — a fork that has not been elevated under
    clause 26b remains subject to clause 26's restrictions regardless of
    what files it has committed. Actions taken in one independent project —
    including ownership transfers, revenue changes, and waivers — have no
    effect on the other. The original Founder's revenue floor carried
    into the fork may be waived or reduced only by a resolution vote among
    the fork's ownership holders, even when the waiver is initiated by the
    original Founder themselves. The original Founder may propose the waiver,
    but it takes effect only once the resolution vote passes and the updated
    CONTRIBUTORS file is committed through the fork's governance process. No
    unilateral act — including a signed waiver record committed without a
    passing resolution vote — has any effect on the floor. A waiver in the
    fork does not affect the original Founder's entitlements in the original
    project. A waiver in the original project does not affect the original
    Founder's carried-over floor in the fork. The forker may not reduce or
    remove the original Founder's floors without such a resolution vote. Any
    person wishing to be listed as a contributor in a fork must be added via
    a resolution vote in the fork, subject to the same governance process as
    the original project.

    At the moment of forking, the fork's ownership holders and their
    respective percentages are identical to those of the original project's
    last validly committed CONTRIBUTORS file at the moment the fork's initial
    commit is created — not any proposed or pending version. If a vote
    modifying the CONTRIBUTORS file is open in the original project at that
    moment, the proposed CONTRIBUTORS.proposed has no effect on the fork
    regardless of how that vote subsequently resolves. The fork is not
    retroactively updated if an open vote later passes in the original
    project. Ownership in a fork is exclusively determined by that inherited
    record and subsequently by resolution votes within the fork. The act of
    forking confers no ownership whatsoever — not to the forker, not to any
    other person. The only way to acquire ownership in a fork is to have held
    ownership in the original project at the time of the fork, or to be voted
    in by the fork's ownership holders after the fork. Until such a vote
    occurs, a resolution in the fork is constituted by the same ownership
    holders and percentages carried over from the original project.

    If, at the time of the fork, the succession of any inherited owner has
    not been resolved — because the owner is deceased or permanently
    incapacitated but no successor or heirs have come forward — that owner's
    ownership percentage is held in abeyance. It does not count toward
    quorum calculations, and it cannot be voted on, transferred, or
    redistributed until a valid successor or heir identifies themselves and
    completes the succession process defined in clause 29, or until the
    fork's remaining ownership holders vote to treat the share as abandoned
    and redistribute it via the standard dilution mechanics. Any revenue share
    held by the same owner is likewise suspended: the fork must hold all
    amounts that would have been payable to that owner in escrow and may not
    distribute them to any other party until the succession is resolved. Upon
    resolution, accrued escrow is released to the confirmed successor or heir.
    If the share is redistributed after the 180-day window, accrued escrow is
    distributed proportionally among the recipients of the redistributed share.
    An inherited owner's share held in abeyance must be resolved within 180
    days of the fork's initial CONTRIBUTORS file being committed. If no valid
    successor or heir comes forward within that period, the fork's ownership
    holders may call a resolution vote to redistribute the abeyance share via
    standard dilution mechanics under clause 15. This vote may not be called
    before the 180-day window expires unless all remaining ownership holders
    consent in writing. If the fork has only one ownership holder at the time
    the 180-day window expires, that holder already holds 100% of the
    remaining active ownership; the abeyance share is automatically absorbed
    into their ownership at that moment without a vote, and the CONTRIBUTORS
    file must be updated via an Administrative Notice under clause 25.

26b. LEGITIMATE FORK BY RESOLUTION VOTE
    A fork may be elevated to a legitimate independent project — with its
    own governance and an independent ownership and revenue structure — only
    by a resolution vote of the original project's ownership holders. Until
    such a vote passes, any fork of this software remains subject to the
    inherited governance structure defined in clause 26 and confers no
    independent rights on the forker. The minimum 5% ownership requirement
    under clause 8 applies to fork proposals by non-Founder owners.

    Fork queue and vote ordering:
    A fork vote may not be opened while any other vote in the original
    project is open. To initiate a fork vote, the proposer places it in a
    queue by committing a signed fork record to:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_fork-queued-<slug>.fork
    The fork record must be clearsigned by the proposer's registered GPG key
    and must include the proposer's pseudonym, the intended fork slug, and a
    UTC timestamp. From the moment the fork record is committed, no new
    votes of any kind may be opened by any owner in the original project.
    Votes already open at the time of queuing proceed to close normally.
    Once all votes open at the time of queuing have closed, the fork vote
    opens. If no votes were open at the time of queuing, the fork vote opens
    immediately upon the fork record being committed. Only one fork record
    may be active at a time; a second fork record committed while a prior
    one is active has no effect and does not create a second fork vote. The
    second proposer must wait until the first fork vote concludes — or the
    first fork record is voided — before committing their own fork record.
    A queued fork record is irrevocable — it cannot be withdrawn or
    cancelled by the proposer or any other owner after it has been committed,
    except as provided below. The fork vote must be held to conclusion. The
    fork record constitutes the proposer's opening ballot and their YES
    vote on the fork.

    Dormancy deadlock: if a fork record has been queued for 90 or more
    consecutive days and no vote has opened because all remaining votes were
    already open at the time of queuing and have still not closed — due to
    dormancy or any other cause — the fork vote opens automatically at the
    90-day mark regardless of whether prior open votes have closed. Any such
    prior open votes that have not closed by that point are treated as void
    for purposes of unblocking the fork vote only; they continue toward
    their own resolution independently and their outcome in the original
    project is unaffected.

    Bad-faith queue exception: if the ownership holders — excluding the
    proposer — unanimously conclude that the fork record was committed
    without a legitimate purpose, with the intent to freeze governance and
    harass or coerce other owners, they may void it by committing a
    clearsigned joint declaration to:
      governance/votes/<YYYY-MM-DD>_fork-queued-<slug>.void
    signed by each non-proposer ownership holder. The queue is lifted
    immediately upon the last required signature being committed. Voiding
    a fork record constitutes a finding of bad-faith governance against
    the proposer under clause 32 and the Founder must initiate a
    termination vote within 60 days. The 30-day per-subject cooldown under
    clause 8 applies from the date the void record is committed.

    If the proposer becomes unable to act after committing the fork record —
    due to death, permanent incapacitation, key compromise, or any other
    reason — the irrevocability of the fork record means the vote must
    proceed to conclusion, not that it lapses. The remaining ownership
    holders proceed to cast their ballots and the vote resolves on the
    basis of those ballots alone. The proposer's inability to act further
    does not void the vote or lift the queue.
    If the fork vote fails, the queue is lifted immediately and voting in
    the original project resumes normally. While the fork vote is open,
    new votes may be opened in the original project; any such votes proceed
    in the original project only and do not carry over to the fork regardless
    of outcome.

    To initiate a legitimate fork, the proposer must submit a proposed
    CONTRIBUTORS file for the fork at the time the fork vote is opened. The
    proposed CONTRIBUTORS file is a required file for the vote — the vote is
    invalid without it — and must be listed with its BLAKE3 hash in the Files
    section of the vote record. The proposed CONTRIBUTORS file must specify:

      a) The complete initial ownership and revenue partition for the fork,
         expressed as percentages summing to 100% for each, covering all
         parties who will hold a share in the fork. Floors and undiluted
         shares must be stated explicitly.

      b) The Founder of the fork. If no new Founder is designated, the
         original Founder carries over as the fork's Founder. Designating
         a new Founder is optional — the fork may retain the same Founder
         or any other existing ownership holder in that role. If a new
         Founder is designated, that person must have explicitly consented
         in writing before the fork vote is opened; their consent must be
         included as a signed statement in the fork vote record or committed
         to the vote folder as a separate clearsigned file. A designation
         without documented consent is void and the fork's proposed
         CONTRIBUTORS file is invalid.

      c) The original project's revised ownership and revenue partition,
         if any ownership or revenue is being transferred out of the original
         project as part of this vote. Absent explicit transfer, the original
         project's CONTRIBUTORS file is unchanged.

    The legitimate fork vote may concern both the fork's proposed CONTRIBUTORS
    file and the original project's revised CONTRIBUTORS file as a permitted
    bundled vote, provided both are explicitly stated in the vote description
    and slug.

    When the vote passes:
      - The forker must create the fork repository and commit the fork's
        CONTRIBUTORS file exactly as approved within 48 hours of the vote
        closing. This window may be extended only in the circumstances
        described below; in all other cases it is hard. If the fork
        repository is not created and the CONTRIBUTORS file not committed
        within that window, the vote lapses. A lapsed fork vote is subject
        to the standard 30-day per-subject cooldown under clause 8 before
        a new fork vote may be opened.

        Force majeure: if the forker is unable to execute the fork commit
        within the 48-hour window due to circumstances entirely outside
        their control — including extended outage of the hosting platform
        designated in the vote record, natural disaster, or government
        action — the window is paused for the duration of the impediment
        and resumes when the impediment ends. The forker must document the
        impediment by committing a signed statement to the original
        repository within 24 hours of the window expiring, identifying the
        impediment and its dates. If no such statement is committed, the
        lapse stands and the cooldown applies. Disputes over whether an
        impediment qualifies as force majeure are resolved by a resolution
        vote of the original project's ownership holders.

        If the proposer becomes permanently incapacitated or dies after the
        vote passes but before the 48-hour window expires, any other
        ownership holder may execute the fork commit on behalf of the
        ownership group, provided they do so within the same 48-hour window.
        The substitute executor must commit the CONTRIBUTORS file exactly as
        approved and include in the same commit a signed statement attesting
        to the proposer's incapacitation or death. This exception does not
        extend the 48-hour window; if no remaining owner acts within it, the
        vote lapses and the 30-day cooldown applies.
      - The fork's Founder ownership floor defaults to 30% unless the vote
        explicitly sets a different value.
      - The original Founder's revenue floor in the fork, as defined in
        clause 26, may be reduced or removed only if this fork vote
        explicitly grants a waiver. A post-fork waiver requires a separate
        resolution vote in the fork under the mechanics defined in clause 26.
        Absent an explicit grant, the floor carries over unchanged.
      - All governance artifacts from the original project must be copied
        into the fork's repository under the governance/ folder, preserving
        the full record of how the fork was authorised. This includes all
        in-progress vote folders: any vote that was open in the original
        project at the time of the fork must be copied in its current state
        — including the .vote file and all ballots already committed — as a
        historical record. Such in-progress votes have no binding effect on
        the fork: they do not transfer governance obligations, and their
        outcome in the original project has no retroactive effect on the
        fork's governance or CONTRIBUTORS file. Deliberate omission of any
        governance artifact constitutes bad-faith governance under clause 32.
        An accidental or incomplete copy is curable: the forker must commit
        the missing artifacts within 30 days of the omission being
        identified. Failure to cure within that period is treated as
        deliberate omission.
      - From the moment the fork's CONTRIBUTORS file is committed, the fork
        is an independent project governed exclusively by its own ownership
        holders under this license.

    A legitimate fork does not sever the original project. Both projects
    continue independently, each governed by their own CONTRIBUTORS file
    and ownership holders from that point forward.

    Fork of a fork: once a legitimate fork is established under this clause,
    it is a normal independent project for all purposes of this license. Any
    subsequent fork of that project follows the same rules as forking any
    project under clauses 26 and 26b, with the fork's own Founder and
    CONTRIBUTORS file as the authoritative record. The original project's
    Founder has no automatic claim in grandchild forks — their carried-over
    floor under clause 26 applies only to direct forks of the original project
    and does not cascade transitively into further generations. Any revenue
    obligation the original Founder holds in a direct fork — by virtue of
    the carried-over floor — remains in force within that direct fork
    regardless of any subsequent fork of that direct fork. A sub-fork of a
    direct fork is a separate project; it carries no inherited obligation
    to the original Founder, and the direct fork's own revenue obligations
    to the original Founder are unaffected by the existence or commercial
    activity of that sub-fork.

