TRADEMARKS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

27. NO TRADEMARK GRANT
    This license does not grant any rights to use the Founder's name,
    pseudonym, project name, logos, or any associated marks, whether
    registered or unregistered. No such rights are implied by the terms
    of this license.

28. FORK NAMING RESTRICTION
    A fork of this software may not use the original project's name, or any
    name confusingly similar to it, or present itself as the official version
    of the original project, without written permission granted by a
    resolution vote of the original project's ownership holders under the
    governance process defined in clauses 19–25.

    Once a fork is a legitimate independent project under clause 26b, this
    restriction applies in both directions: neither project may adopt a name
    confusingly similar to the other without a resolution vote of the
    project whose name is being used or imitated. A resolution vote in the
    fork's governance process grants permission for the fork's own name
    choices; it does not grant permission to use the original project's
    name. A resolution vote in the original project's governance process
    grants permission for the fork to use a name similar to the original;
    it does not constrain the fork's internal governance.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SUCCESSION
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

29. SUCCESSION
    Ownership and revenue share are heritable independently. Any holder may
    designate separate successors for each via the Successor-Ownership and
    Successor-Revenue fields in the CONTRIBUTORS file. The
    Successor-Ownership field is present only for holders with a non-zero
    ownership percentage or patent holdings; the Successor-Revenue field is
    present only for holders with a non-zero revenue share. Both fields are
    optional.

    Permanent incapacitation is defined in the Definitions section. The
    physician's certification must be presented to the remaining ownership
    holders before succession takes effect.

    Upon the death or permanent incapacitation of a holder:
      - Their ownership percentage and patent holdings pass to their
        designated Successor-Ownership. If no Successor-Ownership is named,
        ownership and patent holdings pass to their legal heirs in accordance
        with applicable inheritance law.
      - Their revenue share passes to their designated Successor-Revenue.
        If no Successor-Revenue is named, the revenue share passes to their
        legal heirs in accordance with applicable inheritance law.

    Successor-Ownership and Successor-Revenue may name different people.
    A holder's legal heirs receive only what the holder did not explicitly
    designate to a named successor.

    The successor or heirs must notify the remaining ownership holders and
    update the CONTRIBUTORS file via the standard governance process within
    90 days of the triggering event. For death, the triggering date is the
    date on which the remaining ownership holders first receive written
    notification supported by a death certificate or equivalent legal
    document. For permanent incapacitation, the triggering date is the date
    the physician's certification is presented to the remaining ownership
    holders. If no notification is received within that period, the
    ownership percentage and revenue share are held in abeyance under the
    same mechanics defined in clause 26 for inherited owners in forks, until
    a valid successor or heir comes forward. An inherited share held in
    abeyance must be resolved within 180 days of the triggering event. If no
    valid successor or heir comes forward within that period, the remaining
    ownership holders may call a resolution vote to redistribute the abeyance
    share via standard dilution mechanics under clauses 14 and 15. This vote
    may not be called before the 180-day window expires unless all remaining
    ownership holders consent in writing.

    Declined succession: if a designated successor notifies the remaining
    ownership holders in writing that they decline the inheritance before
    the 90-day window closes, their designation lapses immediately. The
    declined entitlement then passes to the holder's legal heirs as if no
    successor had been named. Declination is per-entitlement-type: a
    successor designated separately for ownership and for revenue may
    independently accept or decline each. A successor designated for both
    in a single combined designation must accept or decline both together;
    they may not partially accept a single combined designation.

    Succession by existing owner: if the designated successor already holds
    ownership or revenue share in the same project, the inherited entitlement
    is added to their existing share. This addition is recorded via an
    Administrative Notice under clause 25 rather than a resolution vote.
    No owner may object on policy grounds to the arithmetic combination;
    only factual errors in the calculation are grounds for objection.

    Commercial rights upon Founder's death or incapacitation: if the
    Founder is deceased or permanently incapacitated and no Commercial Agent
    was designated at the time of the triggering event, the confirmed
    Successor-Revenue holder inherits the right to negotiate and execute
    commercial agreements on behalf of the Founder's revenue share. This
    right is limited to the inherited revenue share only and is subject to
    a resolution vote by the remaining ownership holders before any
    commercial agreement is executed. If the Founder's succession is
    unresolved and no Successor-Revenue can be confirmed, commercial
    agreements requiring the Founder's participation are suspended until
    succession is complete.

    Operational continuity during contested Founder succession: while the
    Founder's succession is unresolved, the following rules apply to
    Founder-specific rights. (a) Default notices under clause 3 are sent
    by the remaining ownership holders acting collectively; any one owner
    may send the notice on the collective's behalf, provided a record of
    that delegation is committed to the repository. (b) The audit right
    under clause 35 is exercised by the remaining ownership holders
    acting by resolution vote. (c) Revenue owed to the Founder under any
    active commercial agreement is held in escrow by the remaining ownership
    holders and released to the confirmed successor or heir upon resolution
    of succession. (d) No new commercial agreement may be executed in the
    Founder's name until succession is confirmed or a Commercial Agent is
    appointed under clause 45.

    Contested or ambiguous entitlements: if the rightful recipient of any
    entitlement cannot be determined — due to legal dispute, absence of
    heirs, ambiguous or conflicting designations, declination by all named
    successors and heirs, or any other reason — all contested entitlements
    revert to the Founder and are held by the Founder pending resolution by
    a competent legal authority or a resolution vote of the remaining
    ownership holders. This applies to ownership, revenue share, and patent
    holdings independently or together. Any entitlement of value that lacks
    a valid, identified, and willing recipient belongs to the Founder by
    default. If the Founder is the deceased or permanently incapacitated
    party whose succession is contested, this fallback does not apply; the
    contested entitlement is held in abeyance by the remaining ownership
    holders and resolved exclusively by applicable inheritance law or a
    competent legal authority, with no internal default recipient.

    Simultaneous incapacitation of all owners: if all ownership holders
    are simultaneously deceased or permanently incapacitated such that no
    active owner remains to conduct governance, the following rules apply.
    The last validly committed CONTRIBUTORS file remains the authoritative
    record of ownership and revenue entitlements. All active commercial
    agreements are suspended from the date the last active owner becomes
    unavailable; no commercial rights may be exercised until at least one
    valid successor or heir is confirmed. The confirmed successors and heirs
    of each owner collectively inherit that owner's governance rights and
    must reconstitute governance within 180 days of the last triggering
    event. If no successors or heirs come forward within that period, any
    party who has contributed to the project and holds evidence of a prior
    commercial relationship may apply to a competent court for appointment
    of a trustee to manage the project's commercial obligations. Nothing in
    this paragraph limits any party's right to fork the project under
    clause 26, subject to the license terms.

