ENFORCEMENT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

33. COMMERCIAL VIOLATION
    Violation of the commercial clause — including use without an agreement,
    deliberate obfuscation of the software's presence in a product, or
    relabelling to avoid attribution — revokes all rights granted by this
    license immediately and permanently. The Founder reserves the right to
    pursue compensation for unlicensed commercial use retroactively, limited
    to the five years preceding the date on which the Founder first received
    written documentation of the violation. This limitation does not apply
    where the violation involved deliberate concealment, fraud, or wilful
    misrepresentation, in which case no time limit applies to retroactive
    claims.

34. NO REVENUE THRESHOLD
    There is no minimum revenue threshold for the commercial use requirement.
    Any use that satisfies the commercial use definition in clause 3 requires
    a prior agreement with the Founder regardless of revenue amount. There
    are no exemptions based on revenue size, project scale, or intent once
    the use is commercial.

35. AUDIT RIGHT
    The Founder, or a representative designated by a resolution vote, may
    request from a commercial licensee a written statement of revenue
    derived from use of this software, covering any period within the
    preceding 24 months. The licensee must respond within 30 days of
    receiving the request. The request may be made at most once per
    calendar year per licensee. If the licensee fails to respond within 30 days
    of receiving the request, or provides a response that omits any required
    field, the Founder may suspend all rights granted by the commercial
    agreement and treat the non-response as a commercial violation under
    clause 33.

    If the Founder is deceased or permanently incapacitated and succession
    is unresolved, the audit right is exercised by the remaining ownership
    holders acting collectively by resolution vote. Any revenue statement
    received during contested succession is held by the remaining ownership
    holders until a valid successor or heir is confirmed, at which point it
    is delivered to that party.

    The written revenue statement must include, at minimum:

      - Time period: the calendar start and end dates of the period covered.
      - Gross revenue: total revenue generated during the period from all
        activities in which the software was a direct or material input,
        before any deductions.
      - Net revenue attributable: revenue net of directly associated costs
        (e.g., hosting fees, third-party licensing fees required solely to
        operate the software), with each deduction itemised and labelled.
      - Basis of calculation: a plain-language description of how the
        software's contribution to revenue was identified and measured,
        including the methodology used to apportion revenue where the
        software is one of several inputs to a product or service.
      - Product or service description: the name and nature of each product
        or service in which the software was used during the period.
      - Signatory: the statement must be signed — physically or by a
        recognised digital signature — by a person with legal authority to
        bind the licensee.

    A statement that omits any required field, or that contains figures the
    Founder has reasonable grounds to believe are materially inaccurate,
    may be treated as a commercial violation under clause 33.

