    to all jurisdictions that are signatories to the Berne Convention for
    the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works, as amended, and to any
    other applicable international copyright treaty. The Founder reserves
    the right to enforce this license and pursue remedies in any jurisdiction
    where a violation occurs or where the violator operates or holds assets,
    without waiving the right to pursue remedies in any other jurisdiction.
    Parties who cannot resolve a dispute through good-faith negotiation agree
    to submit to binding arbitration under the WIPO Arbitration Rules before
    resorting to litigation. The seat of arbitration shall be Madrid, Spain.
    Proceedings shall be conducted in English unless all parties agree
    otherwise in writing. The number of arbitrators shall be one, unless a
    party requests a three-arbitrator panel within 15 days of the notice of
    arbitration being filed, in which case three arbitrators shall be
    appointed in accordance with the WIPO Arbitration Rules. Nothing in this
    clause limits either party from seeking emergency injunctive or other
    equitable relief from a court of competent jurisdiction to prevent
    irreparable harm pending arbitration.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SIGNATURES AND LEGAL WEIGHT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

41. GPG SIGNATURES AS CONSENT
    A GPG-signed ballot, as defined in clause 21, constitutes a binding
    expression of consent by the signing party under this license. By
    signing a ballot, the signing party confirms they have read, understood,
    and agree to be bound by the decision being voted on. GPG clearsign
    signatures produced in accordance with this license are intended to serve
    as evidence of consent and may carry probative weight as electronic
    signatures in applicable legal proceedings. They are not represented as
    qualified or advanced electronic signatures under the eIDAS Regulation
    (EU) 910/2014 unless the signing party has separately obtained a
    certificate meeting the technical requirements of that regulation. The
    parties agree that GPG signatures produced under this license shall be
    treated as a sufficient form of digital signature for the purposes of
    internal governance and may be admitted as evidence in any arbitral or
    judicial proceeding governed by this license.

42. CONTRIBUTORS FILE AS RECORD
    The CONTRIBUTORS file, maintained in accordance with clause 18 and
    amended only through the governance process defined in clauses 19–25,
    constitutes the authoritative record of ownership and revenue
    entitlements under this license. Parties listed therein are bound by
    its contents. Changes made outside the defined governance process have
    no legal effect. Any attempt to alter, remove, or obscure the
    CONTRIBUTORS file or any governance artifact through version control
    operations — including force-push, history rewrite, tag deletion, or
    branch replacement — is void and constitutes bad-faith governance under
    clause 32. The last validly committed version of the CONTRIBUTORS file,
    as verifiable through the repository's signed commit history, remains
    the authoritative record regardless of any subsequent tampering.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
AI-GENERATED CONTRIBUTIONS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

43. AI CONTRIBUTIONS
    Any AI-generated portion of a contribution — as defined in the
    Definitions section — is not original work of the contributor and does
    not entitle the contributor to any ownership or revenue share on that
    basis. All AI-generated portions of a contribution are deemed to be the
    Founder's contribution for the purposes of this license.

    If a contributor's listing in the CONTRIBUTORS file includes ownership
    or revenue share that was granted wholly or partly on the basis of
    AI-generated work, the ownership and revenue share attributable to those
    AI-generated portions must be subtracted from that contributor's entry
    and transferred to the Founder upon discovery. The correction must be
    made via the governance process defined in clauses 19–25 and recorded
    in the CONTRIBUTORS file. This correction is the primary remedy for
    undisclosed AI-generated work discovered after a contributor has been
    listed. Contributor termination under clause 32 applies in addition to
    correction when the failure to disclose was wilful or where the
    undisclosed portions are so substantial that the correction would
    eliminate the contributor's entire entitlement; it does not replace the
    correction obligation. Where the contributor disclosed in good faith but
    inaccurately, correction without termination is the appropriate remedy.

    Contributors must disclose AI-generated portions at the time of
    submission. Disclosure must be made in the pull request description,
    patch cover letter, or equivalent submission artifact. The disclosure
    must include, at minimum:

      AI-Disclosure: yes
      Tool: <name of the AI tool used, e.g., ChatGPT, GitHub Copilot>
      Scope: <description of which files, functions, or sections were
              produced by the AI tool>

    If no AI tools were used, the contributor must state:

      AI-Disclosure: none

    Omitting the AI-Disclosure field entirely constitutes failure to
    disclose. Failure to disclose constitutes misrepresentation of
    authorship under clause 32 and is grounds for contributor termination.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
GPG KEY ROTATION
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

44. GPG KEY ROTATION
    An ownership holder may replace their registered GPG key by calling a
    key rotation vote. A key rotation vote is a standard resolution vote subject
    to the following special rules:

      - The voting window is governed by the Key Rotation Window definition:
        a maximum of 24 hours, with no minimum floor. The proposer may shorten
        it but not extend it beyond 24 hours.
      - The vote record must state the holder's pseudonym, the fingerprint
        of the current key, and the fingerprint of the proposed new key.
      - The new key must be publicly verifiable (e.g., uploaded to a public
        keyserver or committed to the repository) before the vote is opened.
      - Absence and abstention tracking applies to key rotation votes on the
        same basis as any other vote.

    The CONTRIBUTORS file may only be updated with the new GPG fingerprint
    after the vote passes and all artifacts are committed. Until the vote
    passes, all ballots must be signed with the existing registered key.

    A holder whose registered key is known or suspected to be compromised
    must disclose the compromise to all other ownership holders immediately.
    Casting a ballot with a known-compromised key after disclosure constitutes
    bad-faith governance under clause 32.

    Emergency key replacement: if a holder's registered key is compromised
    such that they no longer control it and cannot sign a ballot to call a
    rotation vote, any other ownership holder may call a key rotation vote on
    the affected holder's behalf. In this case the vote record must state that
    the vote is being called on the holder's behalf, include a written statement
    from the holder (signed by any means the remaining owners accept as
    authentic) attesting to the compromise and identifying the proposed new key,
    and the affected holder is excused from casting a ballot in that vote — they
    are not marked ABSENT and their tracks are not incremented. If the vote
    passes, the CONTRIBUTORS file is updated with the new key. If no other
    owner is willing to call the vote, the affected holder is locked out of
    governance until they recover control of their key or the remaining owners
    act voluntarily.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
COMMERCIAL AGENT AND FOUNDER DORMANCY
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

45. COMMERCIAL AGENT
    The Founder may designate a Commercial Agent as defined in the
    Definitions section. The Commercial-Agent field in the CONTRIBUTORS file
    records the agent's pseudonym and any scope constraints on their
    authority. Designation and removal of a Commercial Agent require a
    resolution vote. Before ownership is shared, the Founder may designate
    or remove a Commercial Agent unilaterally without a formal vote,
    consistent with the Founder's unilateral resolution right under clause 6.

    Scope constraints must be stated in plain language as a parenthetical
    remark in the Commercial-Agent field, for example: "Jane Doe (SaaS
    agreements only, up to €500k annual revenue)." Any constraint not
    explicitly recorded in the CONTRIBUTORS file is not enforceable.
    Disputes over whether an executed agreement violates recorded scope
    constraints are resolved by a resolution vote.

46. FOUNDER DORMANCY
    If the Founder is dormant — as defined in the Founder Dormancy definition —
    the remaining ownership holders may appoint a temporary Commercial Agent
    by resolution vote. The temporary agent's authority is identical to that
    of a designated Commercial Agent under clause 45 and expires:

      a) when the Founder resumes participation and revokes the appointment
         by resolution vote, or
      b) after 12 months, unless renewed by a further resolution vote.

    For the purpose of this appointment vote only, a dormant Founder's
    absence from the ballot is not counted as NO and does not block passage
    of the vote. The dormant Founder's ownership percentage is excluded from
    the ownership snapshot for that specific vote, and quorum is calculated
    against the remaining owners' total ownership.

    The temporary appointment does not affect the Founder's ownership,
    revenue floor, voting rights, or any other entitlement. The Founder
    retains full rights upon resuming participation. Appointment of a
    temporary Commercial Agent does not clear or reset the Founder Dormancy
    condition; the Founder remains dormant until they resume participation
    and cast an active ballot (YES, NO, or ABSTAIN). Being marked EXCUSED
    in a vote does not resolve dormancy, even though it resets the
    consecutive ABSENT counter as defined in the Founder Dormancy
    definition.

    If the Founder becomes permanently incapacitated while dormant, the
    temporary Commercial Agent's appointment expires immediately. Succession
    then proceeds under clause 29, and the temporary agent has no authority
    to act on behalf of the successor until the successor has been confirmed
    through the governance process and has explicitly re-designated the agent.

